

âœ… Is Multiple Inheritance Allowed in Java?

ðŸš« Multiple Inheritance using Classes â€“ Not Allowed

In Java, a class cannot extend more than one class at the same time. This is done to avoid ambiguity, known as the Diamond Problem.

â¸»

ðŸ”º Example â€“ The Diamond Problem:

class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}

class B {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Class B");
    }
}

// âŒ Error â€“ Java does not allow this
class C extends A, B {
    // Compilation Error: Class C cannot extend multiple classes
}

	â€¢	Both class A and B have a method show().
	â€¢	If class C inherits both, which show() should be called?
âž¡ï¸ This creates confusion (ambiguity), so Java doesnâ€™t support multiple class inheritance directly.

â¸»

âœ… Solution: Multiple Inheritance using Interfaces

In Java, you can implement multiple interfaces and even extend one class at the same time.

interface X {
    void methodX();
}

interface Y {
    void methodY();
}

class Base {
    void baseMethod() {
        System.out.println("Base class method");
    }
}

// âœ… Multiple Inheritance using Interface + Single class
class Derived extends Base implements X, Y {
    public void methodX() {
        System.out.println("Method X from Interface");
    }

    public void methodY() {
        System.out.println("Method Y from Interface");
    }
}


â¸»

ðŸ” Key Notes about Java Interfaces
	1.	Interface â‰  Class, but it acts like a blueprint.
	2.	An interface can contain:
	â€¢	Method signatures (abstract methods)
	â€¢	Constants (public static final)
	â€¢	Default and Static methods (from Java 8 onward)
	3.	A class that implements an interface must define all the methods from that interface.
	4.	You can create a reference of an interface type, but not an object.
	5.	All methods in an interface are public and abstract by default (till Java 7).

â¸»

ðŸ”¸ Real-Life Analogy:

Imagine:
	â€¢	RemoteControl is an interface.
	â€¢	TV, AC, Speaker are classes implementing it differently.

This allows different devices to behave according to the same â€œtemplateâ€ (interface).

â¸»

ðŸ“˜ Summary: Multiple Inheritance in Java

Feature	Support in Java
Multiple inheritance using classes	âŒ Not supported
Multiple inheritance using interfaces	âœ… Supported
Class can extend one class	âœ… Yes
Class can implement multiple interfaces	âœ… Yes


â¸»

âœ… Example Summary Code:

interface Animal {
    void eat();
}

interface Bird {
    void fly();
}

class LivingBeing {
    void breathe() {
        System.out.println("Breathing...");
    }
}

class Bat extends LivingBeing implements Animal, Bird {
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Bat eats insects.");
    }

    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Bat flies at night.");
    }
}


â¸»

âœ… Output:

Breathing...
Bat eats insects.
Bat flies at night.


